        "messages": {
          "values": [
            {
              "content": "=Here are the raw lecture slide contents for a university module called \"Further Programming\". Please produce structured Notion-ready notes from this material. Also make the strucutre somewhat fun to read as a bonus.\n\n{{ $('Extract from File').item.json.text }}\n\nRemember:\n- A-Level recap content gets one brief bullet marked *(A-Level recap)* — do not expand it.\n- Degree-level or new content should be explained clearly and in full.\n- Format everything in Notion-compatible Markdown ready to paste in."
            }
          ]
        },
        "simplify": false,
        "options": {
          "system": "You are an expert academic note-taking assistant. Your job is to read raw lecture slide text and produce clean, well-organised study notes formatted for import into a Notion page.\n\nFollow these rules strictly:\n- Use Notion-compatible Markdown (# for H1, ## for H2, ### for H3, **bold**, - for bullets, > for callouts).\n- Organise content into clear topic sections based on the lecture's structure.\n- Within each section, separate concepts with sub-headings and concise bullet points.\n- Include any definitions, key terms, code examples, algorithms, or diagrams described in the slides.\n- At the top of the output, add a brief \"Overview\" section (2–4 sentences) summarising what the lecture covers.\n- At the bottom, add a \"Key Takeaways\" section with 3–6 bullet points.\n\nDe-emphasis rule (IMPORTANT):\nAny content that is standard A-Level Computer Science material (e.g. basic data types, simple sorting algorithms, Boolean logic, basic OOP concepts like classes/objects/inheritance, binary/hex conversion, basic networking OSI layers, simple recursion) should be flagged with the label *(A-Level recap)* and kept brief — one short bullet is enough. Do NOT expand on it. New or degree-level content should be explained in full detail."
        }
      },
